faqs:
  - q: "How does the calculator estimate payoff time?"
    a: "It applies your APR to the current balance each month, subtracts your monthly payment, and rolls the remaining balance forward until it reaches zero. The number of months it takes is your estimated payoff time, and the interest accumulated along the way is your total interest cost."
  - q: "What payment size will pay off my card fastest?"
    a: "Any payment above the minimum accelerates payoff. Doubling the minimum often cuts the payoff time by more than half because more of each payment hits principal instead of interest. Try a few payment levels in the tool to see the tradeoff."
  - q: "Why does paying only the minimum take so long?"
    a: "Minimum payments are designed to barely exceed monthly interest. At a 22.9% APR most of the minimum goes to interest, leaving very little to reduce principal — which is why minimum-only payoff often runs over a decade and costs more in interest than the original balance."
  - q: "Should I use the avalanche or snowball method?"
    a: "Avalanche (highest APR first) saves the most interest mathematically. Snowball (smallest balance first) gives faster psychological wins. Pick the one you'll actually stick with — both work if you maintain consistent extra payments."
  - q: "Does this account for new charges added to the card?"
    a: "No. The estimate assumes you stop adding new charges. If you keep using the card, your real payoff time will be longer than the estimate. Pause new spending while paying down to make the projection accurate."
